text:
aly raisman
olympic gold medalist, gymnastics
hero
__
i grew up idolizing the women of usa gymnastics for their skill, poise, confidence, and superhuman abilities. little did i know, they were so much more than that. this year, aly raisman was one of the women who blew the lid off a decades long history of sexual abuse in the usa gymnasics community. after showing the world what she could do physically, she took the opportunity to make the world listen to what she had to say. along the way, she inspired a whole new generation of women to be strong, and speak out agains abuse and injustice. thank you, aly, for telling your gut-wrenching story. it matters. she, among others, stood up against a global institution, and burned it to the ground.
.
from #vanityfair: few icons of american girlhood are as symbolically complex as elite gymnasts. they appear on the mat as tiny shining birds: gems sewn into their leotards sparkling under bright competition lights, and colorful bows plopped on their french-braided hairdos like feathered crowns. scouts looking for young gymnasts with the potential to reach the olympics sometimes spot girls as young as seven. their careers usually peak before they can vote and end before they can legally order a glass of wine in a restaurant. yet they are athletes of extraordinary accomplishment and fortitude. theyâ€™re strong women, or girls becoming women, who fly through the air seemingly by sheer force of will. as a child glued to the television during the summer olympics in the 1980s, i thought of them as real-life versions of superwoman. women of steel, lighter than air.
.
in recent months, raisman has also assumed the role of captain in this fight. along with a small army of former olympians, including jamie dantzscher and jordyn wieber, she hopes that by speaking out about the factors that led to nassarâ€™s abuse they will ultimately engineer a vast redesign of her sportâ€™s culture. they are a new kind of american hero.
__
#dailyfeminist #alyraismen #olympicgold #gymnastics #usagymnastics #goldmedal #hero #jewishwomen #womensstories #8days #speakout #metoo #timesup #usa #fuckpredetors #burnitdown @alyraisman

text:
grateful that i've had the privilege to share about my idea on @tedxunivindowomen about how we, as a community can actually prevent sexual violence.
as much as i admire the #metoo movement, i feel that it shouldn't be a burden for the victims alone to speak up. we, as part of the society, needs to own up to our responsibility as an active bystander and shows that we're on their side. 
change is more than legislative and organizational policy reform; it's also about the actual day-to-day practice. pay attention to what you are doing to hold yourself and others accountable, and respond if you see or hear about an incident of sexual harassment or abuse. it is time for us to do our part to stop sexual violence.

text:
9)@courtneymelba - â€˜nameless, facelessâ€™â£
one of the positives to come from the #metoo era has been the kick-ass soundtrack, and though this tragicomic anthem was written before the movement, it most definitely captures the temperature of the times. courtney turns her celebrated talent for witty observation towards gallows humour, but the charming melodies and bouncing, fuzzy guitars barely soften the bite of her words or the violence sheâ€™s addressing.â£
â£
â€˜i wanna walk through the park in the dark/men are scared that women will laugh at themâ€™, she sings in the chorus, paraphrasing margaret atwood in a potent lyrical backflip; â€˜women are scared that men will kill them.â€™ coupled with the all-too-relatable image of her keys balled in her fists in self-defence, itâ€™s a devastating portrait of the fear that women commonly experience in what should be the safest of spaces. â£
â£
â€˜nameless, facelessâ€™ is as much an amped-up riposte to toxic online culture as it is misogyny, and while the song doesnâ€™t strictly propose that one always escalates to the other, it shows the two arenâ€™t mutually exclusive either. courtney should know. despite the global adoration behind her debut album, thereâ€™s been a nasty undercurrent of hostility mixed in with the tidal wave of praise. â£
the internet cynics whoâ€™ve barraged the 30yo songwriter with a torrent of negativity and blatantly non-musical insults, are (letâ€™s be real) typically dudes. the unwarranted sexism is exhausting, but courtney transforms it into something empowering. she doesnâ€™t play the victim, she flips the tables, giving those same anonymous online critics a starring role in â€˜nameless, facelessâ€™, undressing their pent-up anger as a symptom of loneliness, frustration, and fragile male ego. she feeds the trolls with kindness, offering her sympathies and even a hug: â€˜iâ€™m real sorry/â€™bout whatever happened to youâ€™. â£
â£
that she wraps all those sentiments and social analysis into a catchy, deadpan indie rock single only proves how accomplished a songwriter courtney barnett has become. breaking the golden rule of the internet - â€˜donâ€™t read the comments!â€™ - didnâ€™t hurt her, it only made her stronger.â£

text:
one of my favourite quotes from lao tzu and so very true. everyone has their own journey and challenges along the way. many of us know where we want to go but our conditioning tells us that it's too hard, or too far away, but if you start placing one foot in front of the other , and taking it one it one step, one breath, one day at a time you will eventually get to where you want to go. i never thought in a million years i'd be where i am today, for so long i was stuck being strangled by my past, the trauma, the pain and i thought i would never be able to get out of it, but here i am today living, loving a life of happiness. i am growing each day, and still taking it one step at a time.

text:
started writing down little victories in this ptsd journal. i'm not always good at journaling consistently. i often do it for a few months, stop, feel like i have to rip out stuff i've written and start over again.

but this time i'm making a conscious effort to not feel like i have to rip up what i've written. i'll be working with my therapist, really digging deep and working on figuring out why i feel like that. perhaps it's because of everything i've been through, the desire for a clean slate i'll never get in real life. the one i've always wanted, and the chance to start over with friendships that i ruined by being too consumed with anger and frustration about what happened to me.

what are you guys journaling about? what do you guys do to fight ptsd?

#ptsd #mentalhealthawareness #sexualabuse #journaling #metoo #selfcare

text:
are you afraid of starting a business, a movement, or sharing your own thoughts with the world because youâ€™re afraid of what other people will think?
.
#metoo!
.
but not anymore. this is who iâ€™m meant to be, this is what iâ€™m passionate about, and i whole heartedly believe my purpose in life is to share what i love with like-minded individuals.
.
lately, iâ€™ve noticed a lot of my old peers taking a step towards doing whatever it is they have been yearning to do in life despite the fear they had jumping into it in the beginning, and theyâ€™re crushing it!
.
so, i thought to myself, why arenâ€™t you doing the same? why are you afraid still? if they can do it, why canâ€™t i?
.
well, i can. the problem was just taking the leap and getting started.
.
can you relate to that? ever wanted to do something so bad, but you were already comfortable with where you were and accepted whatever it was that you believed so you just stayed put? well, let me tell you something, in order to grow, you must be uncomfortable!
.
so here i am, uncomfortable as hell, sharing what i love with all of you because i refuse to be afraid any longer.
.
iâ€™m not sure why we have let society suppress us, for fear of not being liked, or being judged. no one has a right to judge who we are, much less voice their own opinion about what it is that makes us happy.
.
anyways, thatâ€™s my rant! i canâ€™t wait to continue to share what fuels me with all of you in hopes that at least some of you can relate or will learn something from it. thank you to those who have showed their support by sharing my posts, liking my posts, and saying such kind, motivating things. it means so much!

text: the cover story in this weekâ€™s sunday styles section of the @nytimes is a story i worked on with @seligsonh about the recent proliferation of menâ€™s groups such as the @themankindproject and @_evryman_ in context of the #metoo movement, male privilege and toxic masculinity. these groups take many forms, employ a variety of techniques and are taking place all across the country but the main objective seems to be to create a safe space for men to exhibit vulnerability, shame, fear, anger and helplessness in the empathetic company of other men. in the short time i spent with them i saw a remarkable amount of eye contact, authentic participation, attentive listening, explosive rage and uncontrollable sobbing. there may be some disagreement about the methods and models but one thing is clear: there are many men making earnest attempts to improve their emotional awareness and personal accountability. this can only be of benefit not only to them and the other men around them but to the women and children in their lives.

text:
well, how come you only want tomorrow?
with its promise of something hard to do
a real-life adventure
worth more than pieces of gold
blue skies above, sun on your arms
strength in your stride and hope
in those squeaky-clean eyes

you'll get chilly receptions
everywhere you go
blinded with desire
i guess the season is on

so you train by shadow boxing
search for the truth
but it's all, but it's all used up
break open your million-dollar weapon
and push your luck
still you push, still you push your luck
a broken-nosed mogul are you
one of the new-wave boys

same old thing in brand new drag
comes sweeping into view

as ugly as a teenage millionaire
pretending it's a whizz-kid world
you'll take me aside, and say

well, david, what shall i do?
they wait for me in the hallway
i'll say, don't ask me
i don't know any hallways
but they move in numbers
and they've got me in a corner
i feel like a group of one
no, no, they can't do this to me

i'm not some piece of teenage wildlife

those midwives to history
put on their bloody robes
and the word is that the hunted one
is out there on his own

and you're alone
for maybe the last time
and you breathe for a long time
then you howl like a wolf
in a trap and you daren't look behind

you fall to the ground
like a leaf from a tree
and look up one time
at that vast blue sky
scream out of line
as they shoot you down

no, no, i'm not a piece of teenage wildlife

i'm not a piece of teenage wildlife

and no one will have seen
and no one will confess
the fingerprints will prove
that you couldn't pass the test
there'll be others on the line
filing past, who'll whisper low
i miss you, he really had to go
well, each to his own
he was another piece of teenage wildlife

nother piece of teenage wildlife

nother piece of teenage wild

wild

wild

wild

david bowie

text:
well, how come you only want tomorrow?
with its promise of something hard to do
a real-life adventure
worth more than pieces of gold
blue skies above, sun on your arms
strength in your stride and hope
in those squeaky-clean eyes

you'll get chilly receptions
everywhere you go
blinded with desire
i guess the season is on

so you train by shadow boxing
search for the truth
but it's all, but it's all used up
break open your million-dollar weapon
and push your luck
still you push, still you push your luck
a broken-nosed mogul are you
one of the new-wave boys

same old thing in brand new drag
comes sweeping into view

as ugly as a teenage millionaire
pretending it's a whizz-kid world
you'll take me aside, and say

well, david, what shall i do?
they wait for me in the hallway
i'll say, don't ask me
i don't know any hallways
but they move in numbers
and they've got me in a corner
i feel like a group of one
no, no, they can't do this to me

i'm not some piece of teenage wildlife

those midwives to history
put on their bloody robes
and the word is that the hunted one
is out there on his own

and you're alone
for maybe the last time
and you breathe for a long time
then you howl like a wolf
in a trap and you daren't look behind

you fall to the ground
like a leaf from a tree
and look up one time
at that vast blue sky
scream out of line
as they shoot you down

no, no, i'm not a piece of teenage wildlife

i'm not a piece of teenage wildlife

and no one will have seen
and no one will confess
the fingerprints will prove
that you couldn't pass the test
there'll be others on the line
filing past, who'll whisper low
i miss you, he really had to go
well, each to his own
he was another piece of teenage wildlife

nother piece of teenage wildlife

nother piece of teenage wild

wild

wild

wild

david bowie

itâ€™s been a week of accelerated effort and commitments to end violence against women in all its forms.

violence against women in elections is not just a violation of the civic rights of women to vote, be voted for, or participate in the electoral process at various levels, it is a denial of their rights to be part of a free, fair and inclusive democracy. these incidents must be addressed because womenâ€™s rights are primarily human rights. -

text:
i'm fortunate enough to never had the need to use the hashtag #metoo but don't let the fear of societal judgement be the reason another crime goes unreported.
.
sexual harrassment and assault is a criminal offence, irregardless of your sex or gender. no victim should have to feel ashamed to report a crime just because society finds any feasible excuse to justify such heinous acts. it's time to stop gender stereotyping and start thinking logically about this. doesn't hurt to have a little common sense, now does it?
.

text:
itâ€™s been a week of accelerated effort and commitments to end violence against women in all its forms. 
we participated at an interactive session on ending violence against women in elections. kudos to @unwomen @unwomen_africa @unwomennigeria on the launch of the programming guide on ending violence against women in elections (vawe). violence against women in elections is not just a violation of the civic rights of women to vote, be voted for, or participate in the electoral process at various levels, it is a denial of their rights to be part of a free, fair and inclusive democracy. these incidents must be addressed because womenâ€™s rights are primarily human rights. -

violence against women in elections is not just a violation of the civic rights of women to vote, be voted for, or participate in the electoral process at various levels, it is a denial of their rights to be part of a free, fair and inclusive democracy. these incidents must be addressed because womenâ€™s rights are primarily human rights. -

text:
itâ€™s been a week of accelerated effort and commitments to end violence against women in all its forms. 
we participated at an interactive session on ending violence against women in elections. kudos to @unwomen @unwomen_africa @unwomennigeria on the launch of the programming guide on ending violence against women in elections (vawe). in pic: group pix of discussants at the launch. 
violence against women in elections is not just a violation of the civic rights of women to vote, be voted for, or participate in the electoral process at various levels, it is a denial of their rights to be part of a free, fair and inclusive democracy. these incidents must be addressed because womenâ€™s rights are primarily human rights. -

text:
recently, i have been reasoning through the fear, obligation, and guilt i had during my relationship. before i understood what was happening, i felt a moral obligation to stay. he would quote scripture saying i had no biblical reason to divorce. i felt fearful when he told me no one else cared, he was the reason i had a car, a phone etc. i felt guilty when he tried to make me think i was just as bad as him or that i should be more forgiving. when i left for the last time, he used the usual tactics (fake apologies, gifts, proclaiming his love). once he realized i wasnâ€™t coming back, he came after me with everything he had. heâ€™s threatened to show family members texts where i complained about them out of anger or ignorance, heâ€™s threatened to expose intimate photos of me from our marriage in court, heâ€™s projecting his alcohol use onto me, requesting my medical records (since i took an antidepressant about three years ago), and he is smearing my name to make me sound unstable. itâ€™s hard to comprehend how someone you thought you loved and could trust would intentionally hurt you and try to make you fearful. i have had a hard time forgiving myself for the mistakes i made, but understand that i was groomed and manipulated very easily. 
the best thing i have done for myself is to be 100% truthful. i have told my family everything i could have possibly said about them, iâ€™ve exposed any drinking or smoking that occurred with this man, and iâ€™ve been honest about the darkest details of the relationship. i am so grateful and undeserving of a family who stands by me through this storm. they know the mistakes iâ€™ve made and it has only made us more faithful. i am not afraid to expose myself in the process of exposing him. if he shows others nude photos of me, that were meant for my husband, i will live. i know i am well and i am stable. i have made mistakes, but i am not a criminal and i am not abusive.âœŒğŸ»#narcissisticabuse #narcissisticpersonalitydisorder #psychopathfree #metoo #sociopath #npd #healingfromhiddenabuse #fearobligationguilt

text:
the recent #metoo movement in india has made one thing very clear: many victims of workplace sexual harassment are more comfortable posting about their experiences on social media than filing a formal complaint. among them are also ones that have resorted to social media only because they did not get justice through the law.

this is hardly surprising as the current sexual harassment law in india does offer perpetrators several loopholes to escape. moreover, even though many organisations are not fully compliant with the law, they are yet to be penalised.

be.artsy helps companies successfully prevent sexual harassment at the workplace with the support of the existing law and not by depending completely on it. for more information, write to:Â shipra@be-artsy.com. .

text:
itâ€™s been a week of accelerated effort and commitments to end violence against women in all its forms. 
we participated at an interactive session on ending violence against women in elections. kudos to @unwomen @unwomen_africa @unwomennigeria on the launch of the programming guide on ending violence against women in elections (vawe). in pic: nigeria country rep. un women, ms. comfort lamptey with our founder @inimfonetuk (r) and our head of contacts mrs. tochi aguiyi-akujua @lynongod at the launch. 
violence against women in elections is not just a violation of the civic rights of women to vote, be voted for, or participate in the electoral process at various levels, it is a denial of their rights to be part of a free, fair and inclusive democracy. these incidents must be addressed because womenâ€™s rights are primarily human rights. -

day 15 | december 09 
because we have accepted to hide the abuse we suffer, because we have decided to be silent through the hurt. because we donâ€™t speak loud enough or often enough. because of the fear, the tears and the stares. but no more! 
it is time to hear me too, it is our time to stand up and fight against any abuse or violation of any girl, woman or child. we will no longer sit still and be silent. 
we will honour ourselves by standing up and speaking as we take back our power.

the time is now. it is time for change!
.

christmas is in full swing over here after a day packed full of the festive feels yesterday! and this one took it all in her stride with minimal moaning â¤ï¸ and despite huge amounts of distraction and quite a blip in our toileting journey only 2 very small toileting accidents! #winning .
our day started with party prep followed by partying hard with friends, disco lights, father christmas and numerous crafts (very proud to say all the glitter you see in this picture is glitter left from previous years... none new bought this year and once its gone, its gone!) followed by a cheeky trip to the pub with our lovely nursery team finished off with a cheese and wine night with family â¤ï¸ if that's not festive, i don't know what is!
.
of course, our day yesterday was bitter sweet..... a year ago we lost our baby, our much wanted, much loved baby and i spent my first night away from arabella while in hospital. needless to say i held her extra tight all day and night yesterday and i will continue to do so today as we remember our beautiful baby ewan â¤ï¸

text:
dr shruti kapoor is an award-winning gender equality activist, economist, and social entrepreneur who is passionate about the safety of girls and women. shaken by the horrific gang rape in delhi 2012, she founded her organisation, sayfty, in june 2013 to educate and empower the women and girls of india against violence. the initiative aims at creating awareness of laws and legal rights around the issue of violence against women. it also uses digital media, tech-for-good, and storytelling to advocate for womenâ€™s safety. 
in 2016, the white house nominated dr kapoor as a change-maker for the united state of women summit 2016. sayfty was awarded the peopleâ€™s choice award by femverstising (2015) and won a state recognition award by the uttar pradesh government in india for the organizationâ€™s work on safety and education of girls. 
dr kapoor holds a phd in economics from the university of california. she has consulted at un women and the world bank in washington dc. she has also served as an adjunct professor of economics at occidental college in los angeles. more recently, she served on the un inter-agency network on youth development working group on youth and gender equality task force and social media committees to inaugurate the united nations youth forum for the commission on the status of women. dr kapoor is also a regular contributor on gender issues and network member of apolitical, a global policy platform and a network of policymakers and thought leaders.

dr kapoor has addressed many national and international public forums including the youth assembly at the united nations, the world woman summit, the world urban forum, and merit 360. she is dedicated to using digital media to raise awareness and make our cities safer for women and girls. (words adapted from http://sayfty.com/about-our-founder/) image: adapted from sayfty.com

dr kapoor holds a phd in economics from the university of california. she has consulted at un women and the world bank in washington dc. she has also served as an adjunct professor of economics at occidental college in los angeles. more recently, she served on the un inter-agency network on youth development working group on youth and gender equality task force and social media committees to inaugurate the united nations youth forum for the commission on the status of women. dr kapoor is also a regular contributor on gender issues and network member of apolitical, a global policy platform and a network of policymakers and thought leaders.

dr kapoor has addressed many national and international public forums including the youth assembly at the united nations, the world woman summit, the world urban forum, and merit 360. she is dedicated to using digital media to raise awareness and make our cities safer for women and girls. text:
today marked 70 years of the universal declaration of human rights, it proclaimed a historic universal norm that we are all born free and equal in dignity and rights. however, today, in many parts of the world,  even in my country, those who are different are still not treated with dignity and respect. their freedom is abused and they are considered as less of a human being.  refugees are viewed as "invaders", lgbti+ is called "disease", those profess to different interpretation of religion are categorized as infidels, indigenous people are marginalized and women are still imprisoned by patriarchy. persecution is assumed as heroic and discrimination is a part of "culture". many things have changed in 70 years,  but circumstances are nowhere near our vision.  it's time for us to speak up more!  i know that we have spoken up,  but it's not enough,  we must speak up louder and unite our voices!

text:
for those 87 million people probably wondering what was actually done with their data, i went back to christopher wylie, the ex-cambridge analytica employee who blew the whistle on the companyâ€™s problematic operations in the observer. according to wylie, all you need to know is a little bit about data science, a little bit about bored rich women, and a little bit about human psychology.

step one, he says, over the phone as he scrambles to catch a train: - when youâ€™re building an algorithm, you first need to create a training set. that is: no matter what you want to use fancy data science to discover, you first need to gather the old-fashioned way. before you can use facebook likes to predict a personâ€™s psychological profile, you need to get a few hundred thousand people to do a 120-question personality quiz.

the â€œtraining setâ€ refers, then, to that data in its entirety: the facebook likes, the personality tests, and everything else you want to learn from. most important, it needs to contain your â€œfeature setâ€: - the underlying data that you want to make predictions on, wylie says. - in this case, itâ€™s facebook data, but it could be, for example, text, like natural language, or it could be clickstream data â€“ the complete record of your browsing activity on the web. - those are all the features that you want to [use to] predict. at the other end, you need your target variables, the things that youâ€™re trying to predict for. so in this case, personality traits or political orientation, or what have you.

alex hern
the guardian

text: calluses. part 1. when i was 12 yrs old i started to burry feelings, some of them in unmarked graves. around that time i was going through so much turmoil and no parental protection, support or guidance. i developed trichotillomania, pulling hair out of my skin because the pain made me feel something. anything. i wasnâ€™t much of the cutter, but i did walk around the school yard with few other lost boys carrying a disposable razor blade inside my mouth. flipping it in circles with my tongue and sliding it out like a snake looking for trouble. i was 13 then. by the time i was 16 i already had scars on my skin from cigarette burns. i no longer self-inflict pain however, iâ€™m not removed from it whatsoever. for example, tattoos are therapeutic for me in the same manner the retreat is therapeutic to a deeply spiritual person. i sought attention in the form of love i wasnâ€™t getting anymore and iâ€™ve found it among those, whose souls resembled stained, wrinkled treasure maps with not enough clues and directions. i grew into desensitized man. very few things will affect me emotionally today. looking at the positive aspect of this, calluses can represent hard work, determination, dedication, purpose, persistence and growth. when i find myself pealing back leather skin at the top corner on the inside of my palms, iâ€™m reminded to leave it alone. (continued from the previous post...) whatever feeling is buried in shallow ground will find itâ€™s way out. i formed tough skin because it meant survival on the psychological and emotional level. everyone has past that can be dug up. no person is free of stains. we all have said and done things in our short lives that had left impact on others both indirectly and directly. but we all change. some for better and some for worse, but we all change. how iâ€™m living today is lightyears away from who i was 5, 10, 15, 25 yrs ago. iâ€™ve changed lifestyles, and careers, iâ€™ve experimented with music, sex and drugs. iâ€™ve hurt people and stole from some. iâ€™ve gotten hurt by people and got robbed by some. i grew and i keep growing. i learned to allow myself to be coachable. people are judged by observation on who they are becoming, what are they building and how theyâ€™re contributing to society. they are also judged by their past. anyone is welcome to dig in between pages of my book. i invite you to read between the cursive lines. in these hypersensitive times and extreme lack of compassion and empathy, in the world so beautiful and promising, we are all sinners. iâ€™m neither overly sensitive, nor do i seek comfort in pain. to play with me you will need to be ok with looking in your own reflection of the water that stands still. you will have to be happy with your own reflection should you choose to skip rocks.

through the mythological story of ahalya, this narrativeâ€™s attempt is to recite the ancient wisdom that helps build the much-needed inner strength to handle difficult situations. this work includes disclosures from indian puranas on the topic of womanâ€™s bondage to a man. it also includes the narratives pertaining to â€˜brahma rahasiyaâ€™ (the eternal secret) as declared in the ancient spiritual texts. 
the spark for this speculative fiction stems from a question â€“ â€˜did something similar to this #metoo issue occur during the days of ramayana and mahabharatha?â€™ this piece of work was developed by identifying the gaps in ahalyaâ€™s narrative in bala khanda of valmiki ramayana and attempting to fill it with the tales cryptically provided in uttara khanda. in addition to ramayana, various other ancient indian literature like mahabharata, panchatantra, jataka tales, lotus sutra, devi bhagvatam, and shiva purana were used in imagining and developing this narrative. 
the well-known sanskrit hymn that defines the panchakanys runs:

"what we are naming with the impetus of #metoo is, at best, an opening to a long-term cultural reckoning to grow up humanity; to make our society more whole. we explore this with psychotherapist avi klein, who works with men and couples, and feminist journalist rebecca traister. in a room full of journalists, at the invitation of the solutions journalism network, we explored how to build the spaces, the imaginative muscle, and the pragmatic forms to support healing for women and men, now and in time."
https://onbeing.org/programs/rebecca-traister-avi-klein-metoo-through-a-solutions-lens-dec2018/
#onbeing

text:
i find that after past traumas surface, it takes several days for me to recalibrate my emotions. my sensitivity is heightened. i start looking for meaning in things that i didn't look for before.
.
i took this photo flying somewhere over the pacific ocean. after everything that happened this past week, i looked at this photo and started crying. i've traveled to so many places all over the earth since i reported that sexual assault in early 2014 and the whole time i believed i'd never get justice. but i was resilient enough to become a world traveler, a business owner, and an outspoken activist anyway.
.
i guess i realized that i didn't need justice from my trauma to rise above it.
-
#worldtraveler #travel #pacific #sunrise #sky #sexualassaultsurvivor #metoo #lifestyle #influencer #bossbabe #writer #activist #feminist #humanist

setelah memenangkan penghargaan di ffi 2015 lalu dan beberapa penghargaan festival film di luar negeri, film siti karya @eddie_cahyono akan kembali diputar di hari terakhir enam belas film festival bali!

film yang kental dengan isu perempuan di masyarakat ini juga menggambarkan seseorang yang bimbang akan pilihannya hidupnya. lalu bagaimanakah kelanjutan kisah siti? saksikan hanya di enam belas film festival bali pada closing night, yang akan dimeriahkan oleh acoustic performance dari penyanyi dan penulis lagu berdarah filipina-amerika @sandrayatifay diikuti penampilan teater oleh @teaterkalangan.

hari: senin, 10 desember 2018
jam: registrasi dibuka pukul 16.00 wita
venue: cushcush gallery, jalan teuku umar gg. rajawali 1a, denpasar

festival ini gratis dan jangan lupa membawa tumbler/botol sendiri, karena acara ini berkomitmen zerowaste.

sampai jumpa di closing night #enambelasffestbali!

text:
in 2000 i marched for the first time. i was a freshman in college and excited to be newly elected to the schools lgbt organization. when we got to dc, we were met with signs like these. but also the standard â€˜god hates fagsâ€™ sort. it was ok though because for the first time ever, i was surrounded by hundreds of thousands of gay people. the great aloneness i had felt all my life dissipated a little over those days. â™¥ï¸ those steps forward weâ€™re followed by so many back. i marched backwards through darkness and in the company of unchecked sorrow. i was gay bashed, physically threatened and terrified. i heard lie after lie about my corrupt and abominable soul, and gods hatred of me. worse, i often hated myself. i tried to escape through drugs and unhealthy sex and various forms of self destruction. i was an apologist for the family and communities that made me feel so small. it was only when death was finally on my doorstep that i realized i had to take my power back from the assholes who would rather i just die. â™¥ï¸ i want the transgendered, the gay ones still forced into closets, the triple whammy black lesbians, the gender non conforming children, the queer of all shapes, sizes, colors and types to see their beauty. i want them to see the history behind our movement. i want them to know that the shame society tries to put on us is just a defense mechanism of those in power. if god is real, she made no mistake in your lovely souls, she gifted you this body as canvas for expression, a space to make real your hearts truth. the shape and policing of your genitals is not a godly concern. never trust someone who tells you other wise. love on siblings! â€¢
â€¢
â€¢

my count is three as well, i say, 
making up two girls beside my ex-wife

needlessly, we then get explicit
priding on promiscuous behaviour

elevators, construction sites, 
cliffs, mountains, beaches, 
everything finds a mention

and soon, we are atop the common wall, 
fumbling and then tumbling over, 
a few sorrys landing between the kisses

our saturday nights never have a closure
but on sundays, we try our best
as we argue about our partners

i disapprove of the way 
you speak about your men, 
you, of how i donâ€™t

you roll your eyes
at how forgetful i am
and i, at how forgiving you are

midway, we stop with the words, 
quieten down and look away
taking the time 
to roll back to our realities

we canâ€™t be a couple, 
we remind each other
as our naked bodies pull away
slowly, reluctantly 
with a voice that breaks as it speaks

but we persist
we cannot be a couple
not the one we should not be.
.
.
animesh ganguly.

text:
what can we do? â€¢	tell people that violence against women and girls is never ok. â€¢	if you suspect that a woman close to you is being abused, listen to and support her. tell her there are people who want to help. 
howe sound womens centre crisis line: 1-877-890-5711 â€¢	believe women when they tell you theyâ€™ve been raped or abused. donâ€™t ask about their behaviour and what they were wearing. listen to what they say without judging them. women never ask for nor deserve to be raped or abused. â€¢	learn about violence against women and girls and what causes it. your education is a tool to end it. â€¢	remember that silence is affirming. when we choose not to speak out about violence against women (or any other injustice) we are supporting it â€¢	encourage and support those people in your community working to end all forms of violence against women and girls. â€¢	talk to family and community members about how violence and fear of violence affect the daily lives of women and girls. talk about how you can support each other to help end violence. â€¢	make your home violence-free. children who have witnessed or suffered from gender-based violence are more likely to become victims and abusers later in life. â€¢	raise your sons and daughters to be equal and teach them that there is nothing that boys can do that girls cannot. â€¢	volunteer to work with violence against women and girls prevention programs in your community. â€¢	share decision-making with women in your life. discuss things with your partner and respect your partnerâ€™s opinions. â€¢	if you are angry, count to 10 before reacting to something you hear or see. â€¢	if a brother, friend, colleague, classmate or teammate is disrespectful to or is abusing a woman or a girl, do not look the other way â€” instead, find a way to talk about it with them. â€¢	words are very powerful, especially when spoken by people with power over others. donâ€™t use disrespectful words.

this case has been making it's rounds for 3 years. there have been celebrities, hardcore lawyers and documentaries discussing this case. 
read about cyntoia brown's story, watch the documentary, me facing life: cyntoia's story. just fyi: it is infuriating and painful to learn this story. make sure you have support and aren't struggling emotionally when you watch it.

text:
if you're offended by "baby it's cold outside" you're going to have a tough go of it in life. and so are your kids.
â€¢first, you are completely ignoring the fact that the song is 74 years old--when women were ladies and men were gentlemen.
â€¢her "protest" was typical of a way a lady would speak to a man instead of just downing some drinks and hopping into bed with him.
no one seems offended by those kinda lyrics when you hear them on the radio all year long.
men actually had to court women back in those days, a subtle dance that for both men and women no longer exists. sad but true.
â€¢secondly, "what's in this drink?" does not imply that she was roofied, or at least it didn't in 1944. you don't need to be a historian to piece that puzzle together.
â€¢she's sarcastically blaming her indecision on her drink, which again, came with the times. is that not obvious? â€¢should we stop watching the wizard of oz because when they fall asleep in the poppy fields that means dorothy is on heroin? â€¢moreover, what are you worried is going to happen?? that people will hear this song, completely misinterpret the lyrics (as you obviously have) and then decide to go date rape someone?
â€¢i'd like to see the #metoo movement taken seriously. uproar over a holiday song, which clearly was not about abuse, has the opposite effect.
â€¢if you were sexually abused, my heart goes out to you, but aren't we surrounded my far more obvious and offensive material on a daily basis that should be drawing the attention? is this really the right battle to fight?
â€¢or maybe you're worried about your children and what they will think when they hear it? gee, maybe it's the perfect teachable moment to actually sit down and have a conversation with your child about how men and women used to be. most notably, not offended by every little thing that crossed their path. â€¢yes, i agree, rudolph gets bullied in the animated version of "rudolph the red nosed reindeer." aaaaaaand?? wasn't that the point of the whole dang story!!??
â€¢it's the ultimate story of redemption and turning the other cheek and doing what you gotta do in the face of adversity.
**continued â¬‡ï¸â¬‡ï¸

text: ahead of every successful man is a woman. that's what i've always believed in. our country and indeed the world we live in consists of so many unsung and under-celebrated brave soldiers, i.e., women. at this women in law seminar, i was able to voice my beliefs regarding the kind of world we could be living in if insecure people stopped creating barriers for women so as to exclude them from shining in their respective fields and areas of talent. there are times when i speak out of anger or out of emotions or after a lot of thinking but here, what i've said comes straight from the heart. victims of sexual harassment find the legal system unwelcoming since those adjudicating upon their sense of violation question back as to what 'type of woman' she was. a bright, young girl gets stabbed 23 times and the defense counsel is only interested in her [quite normal and upright] past 'behaviour'? time to stop excluding women from the legal profession so that there is a turn in the tide of this prevailing injustice. a society which excludes its women can never succeed. a world which excludes women can never progress. #feminism #metoo #protection #inclusivity #black #women #muneebqadir #gender #rights #law #legal #timesup #pakistan

text:
if we didn't already love @michelleobama enough - she only goes and admits that 'she' suffers from #impostersyndrome ğŸ˜³

mrs obama spoke to an audience of 300 students at elizabeth garrett anderson school, islington as part of her worldwide book tour.

she first visited the school nine years ago, when she had only been first lady for a few months. asked how she felt to be seen as a "symbol of hope", mrs obama told the students: "i still have a little (bit of) impostor syndrome, it never goes away, that you're actually listening to me.
"it doesn't go away, that feeling that you shouldn't take me that seriously. what do i know? i share that with you because we all have doubts in our abilities, about our power and what that power is." michelle's honesty has sparked a raft of #metoo responses - although this really doesn't surprise usğŸ˜¢. everyday (sadly) we here so many stories from the mums on our courses about how they have not felt good enough / capable enough or even strong enough . we believe our unique real learning training has given lots of them self belief and the determination to succeed (although we always know you super mums have got it in you - we just help unlock it!). what about you? when have you experienced imposter syndrome and if you managed it - how have you overcome it? or do you have any tips of what we can do when we have moments of self doubt? we'd love to hear from you below ğŸ‘‡ and if you need some support then please do join our empowering women's fb group as we have lots of coaches andfb lives to tackle this very subject as we know how crippling it can be - hit the link in the bio to sign up ğŸ”
.

text:
â€¢ medicalization of childbirth â€“ a case of the stockholm syndrome.
â€¢
increasingly, over-intervention in childbirth is depriving many women of autonomy, strength and even of their physical and mental health.
â€¢
in spite of this well-documented fact, many doctors, midwives, women and ... sadly ... even many feminists confuse the injuries resulting from labor interventions with the dangerous â€œnatureâ€ of birth itself to the extent that the two are almost completely interwoven in the patriarchal narrative that defines childbirth.
â€¢
with such a pervasive and internalized narrative of the female bodyâ€™s fallibility and morbidity, no wonder lay-women can no longer tell whatâ€™s what.
â€¢
most find a defeat by childbirth very likely â€“ and when this defeat occurs you, of course, want to be in a place where you can be rescued...by labor interventions!
â€¢
but what was it that actually caused the child â€œto almost dieâ€? â€¢  or the woman herself â€œto nearly die from postpartum hemorrhageâ€?
â€¢  or other such stories created to boost confidence?
â€¢
...not confidence in the womanâ€™s ability to birth, that is, but rather to boost confidence in her rescue by the very labor interventions that in many cases almost kill her or her baby.
â€¢
as long as the â€œdangerous, sickly, female bodyâ€ appears scarier to us than the vast number of serious injuries caused by labor interventions, patriarchyâ€™s medicalized imprisonment will falsely appear safer to childbearing women.
â€¢
and that, ladies (and gentle men) is the very definition of the stockholm syndrome! â€¢  #sverigeskvinnolobby  #enough #kvinfo  #hric  #informedconsent #birthtrauma  #patriarchy #misogyny #internalizedmisogyny  #obstetricviolence #birthactivism #feminism #feminist #metoo #improvingbirth #empoweredbirth #enough #metoobirth

text:
this weekend i started a new tradition with one of my absolute best friends, @kaitlync123, by my side.

each year, the anniversary of my assault is hard. if iâ€™m being honest, most years i barely even make it out of bed.
but this year, i vowed to validate my progress rather than dwell on the pieces of myself iâ€™m still missing.

so i got outside. i honored my body in the best way i know how. i celebrated what a resilient act of self-love my survival has been.

and i really just wanted to come back to my little sliver of the internet to say thank you for all of your kind words and support this weekend. iâ€™m truly speechless over how well-received my storytelling on survival has been on this platform. thank you for trusting me with your experiences of survival, for believing in me, and mostly, for granting me a positive space to continue my healing.

if youâ€™re reading this as a survivor of sexual assault, please know:
there is no shame in how you tell or donâ€™t tell your story. there is no shame in taking a long time to tell your story. there is no shame in not posting about it publicly. there is no shame in creating boundaries about the details of your assault.

i know how it feels to be shamed for not speaking up, or for not speaking up sooner.
i know that the shame is part of our cycle of victim blaming.

i promise you, thereâ€™s nothing to be ashamed about.
you donâ€™t owe anyone your story, or your advocacy, or your #metoo

if youâ€™re reading as a survivor, please know:
i share my stories of survival for you, but i also share them for me.
my storytelling is part of my reclamation.
it is part of my demanding to be heard, when i was silenced for so long. it is how i take my power back. it is one of my loudest statements of self-love. storytelling has become an integral part of my recovery.
that doesnâ€™t meant itâ€™s part of yoursâ€” 
please remember, healing looks different on everyone.

if youâ€™re reading this as a survivor, please know:
i see you.
i believe you.
i stand in solidarity with you.

maya was raped by an acquaintance a few weeks into her freshman year of college. as is the case for many survivors, maya didnâ€™t immediately identify herself as a victim of sexual violence. she began processing her experience of sexual assault about six months later when she told a friend about what happened. â€œi was describing what happened to me, but i hadnâ€™t put a word to it yet. the person i was talking to said, â€˜he raped you.â€™ thatâ€™s when i first started processing itâ€”when someone else called it out to me and made it more real. it was a big shift in how i had been processing my experience and it became a little easier for me to talk about. i used to try to tone it down for myself, to say i was â€˜taken advantage of.â€™ but now itâ€™s been really important for me to call it what it wasâ€”to use the word rape.â€ donate to rainn: fundraise.rainn.org/25sweaterss
#25daysofsweaters #metoo

text:
iâ€™ve spent the last two saturdayâ€™s celebrating the life of my dear friend aisha millicent fraser who lost her life on november 17th in senseless and brutal act of domestic violence.

itâ€™s taken me some time to make sense of this tragedy and while iâ€™m still in disbelief, i have come to accept what has happened and move on to honor her name and legacy. aisha was such a humble person, it was not until reading her obituary and hearing people speak that i found out all that she had done in her 45 years on this earth. she gave so much to her students, served her community, exposed her daughters to so many wonderful experiences, was a loving daughter and had many amazing experiences of her own. 
one of the many wonderful things that a family member shared about aisha was that she finished everything that she started. this is how she has inspired me immediately. as a person who starts many things but only finishes â€˜someâ€™ i have made a promise to myself to honor aisha by finishing every project that i start moving forward. this is just one of the many ways that my life will become better from the legacy of aisha millicent fraser. she will truly be missed. 
#sayhername
#aishamfraser
#enough
#rememberingaisha

text:
submission from a man addressing other men on the issue of consent/violence: i was in a relationship with a woman who had opened up to me about her sexual assault. he was good friends with the both of us. someone you would never think would do something like this. my first instinct was feeling an overwhelming amount of anger. i wanted something to be done about this. she told me she did not want this to be reported over fear that everyone in our school would find out. it was incredibly hard to constantly have to be around him in school and not being able to say or do anything. it took some time, but i eventually turned that anger into passion. i began teaching courses to multiple high school districts about consent and personal boundaries geared towards young men. it created a conversation about topics these young men have never discussed or thought about. this opened my eyes up to the unfortunate reality all women face and how little these men knew about the issue. i have never met a woman who does not have a story. i'm not perfect and i have made my fair share of mistakes regarding this issues. respect her choice on the matter period, do not make this about yourself. it is her story to tell, not yours. never, under any circumstance, force her to open up about her experience if she is not ready. do not perpetuate the cycle of violence by going after the person, it is not justice by any means. finally, heal. this is not a glamorous journey by any means, but your feelings in this situation matter and they need to be discussed and acknowledged. it is okay to reach out and ask for help. in unity, join women in this fight and become an ally. it starts with you, your actions, and your behaviors. always be conscious of them. change the script and language you use. realize the implications. be present. listen intently. keep growing. please keep fighting. thank you.

#ngocswny #16daysofactivism #hearmetoo #orangetheworld #endvaw #metoo #believesurvivors #wewillnotbesilenced #timesup #standup #consentissexy #consentculture #sexworkiswork #notaskingforit

text:
this is not consent. 
as part of my senior show, the unspoken: voices of the voiceless, i did a performance piece regarding sexual assault. clothing is never an indication of consent to having sex. this is a social critique of victim blaming and the declaration that rape is justifiable dependent on the clothing worn during the assault.  no matter what an individual wears, they should never be subjected to rape, nor should they feel obligated to have sex.

in ireland, a 17 year old girl had her underwear used in a rape case with cousel saying "you have to look at the way she was dressed. she was wearing a thong with a lace front." during this performance, i wore underwear that matched this description. 
this needs to stop. 
#thisisnotconsent #dontfuckingtouchme #metoo #timesup #sexualassaultsurvivor #sexualassault

trauma bonding is a chemical bond created by the intermittent release of stress hormones and pleasure hormones, caused by the abuser running hot and cold or flipping between dr. jekyll and mr. hyde.

the switch between dealing with the nice guy and then the bad guy  confuses your adrenals and creates a rollercoaster of emotions which is quite literally facilitated by the chemicals in your body.

this creates a chemical bond, by the means of which can only be broken by going no contact from the abuser.

text:
what is consent?
consent is an agreement between participants to engage in sexual activity. there are many ways to give consent, and some of those are discussed below. consent doesnâ€™t have to be verbal, but verbally agreeing to different sexual activities can help both you and your partner respect each otherâ€™s boundaries.

how does consent work in real life?
when youâ€™re engaging in sexual activity, consent is about communication. and it should happen every time. giving consent for one activity, one time, does not mean giving consent for increased or recurring sexual contact. for example, agreeing to kiss someone doesnâ€™t give that person permission to remove your clothes. having sex with someone in the past doesnâ€™t give that person permission to have sex with you again in the future.

you can change your mind at any time.
you can withdraw consent at any point if you feel uncomfortable. itâ€™s important to clearly communicate to your partner that you are no longer comfortable with this activity and wish to stop. the best way to ensure both parties are comfortable with any sexual activity is to talk about it.

positive consent can look like this:
- communicating when you change the type or degree of sexual activity with phrases like â€œis this ok?â€
- explicitly agreeing to certain activities, either by saying â€œyesâ€ or another affirmative statement, like â€œiâ€™m open to trying.â€
- using physical cues to let the other person know youâ€™re comfortable taking things to the next level
it does not look like this:
- refusing to acknowledge â€œnoâ€
- assuming that wearing certain clothes, flirting, or kissing is an invitation for anything more
- someone being under the legal age of consent, as defined by the state
- someone being incapacitated because of drugs or alcohol
- pressuring someone into sexual activity by using fear or intimidation
- assuming you have permission to engage in a sexual act because youâ€™ve done it in the past (content for this post was found on the rape abuse and incest national network (rainn) website.)

@regrann from @sheforumafrica - itâ€™s been a week of accelerated effort and commitments to end violence against women in all its forms. 
we participated at an interactive session on ending violence against women in elections. kudos to @unwomen @unwomen_africa @unwomennigeria on the launch of the programming guide on ending violence against women in elections (vawe). in pic: our founder @inimfonetuk facilitating the interactive discussion at the launch. 
violence against women in elections is not just a violation of the civic rights of women to vote, be voted for, or participate in the electoral process at various levels, it is a denial of their rights to be part of a free, fair and inclusive democracy. these incidents must be addressed because womenâ€™s rights are primarily human rights. -

text:
it takes a certain amount of audacity to accuse someone of being a narcissist or a sociopath. an audacity i clearly have. an audacity that has been backed by research, evidence, first-hand experiences, and multiple professional opinions. but not every mean-spirited jerk is a narcissist or a sociopath.
.
i am in no way, shape, or form attempting to silence those who have been personally victimized by a narcissistic sociopath with this post. if you have been victimized by one, i hope you have the same audacity as me to shout it from the rooftops.
.
this is a message for the general public, for those who are misusing these terms on a daily basis due to a lack of education and understanding.
.
gp: please stop throwing out the word â€œnarcissistâ€ to describe your friend that gets botox. please stop throwing around the word â€œsociopathâ€ when you get dumped by someone that wasnâ€™t that into you. you are *potentially* mislabeling people in your lives when the words vain, selfish, dismissive or aloof may have been better suited. the terms narcissist and sociopath are much, much bigger than vanity, entitlement, disinterest and abandonment. they are the sum of these things and more.
.
learn what it truly means to be a narcissist and/or a sociopath and then use those words carefully. if you canâ€™t name at least five of the nine dsm criteria for npd, maybe donâ€™t use the word narcissist at all. when you throw these words around haplessly, you normalize a serious personality disorder which indirectly normalizes and trivializes the trauma they cause their victims. ğŸ’›ğŸ¦‹

text:
@regrann from @sheforumafrica - itâ€™s been a week of accelerated effort and commitments to end violence against women in all its forms. 
we participated at an interactive session on ending violence against women in elections. kudos to @unwomen @unwomen_africa @unwomennigeria on the launch of the programming guide on ending violence against women in elections (vawe). in pic: nigeria country rep. un women, ms. comfort lamptey with our founder @inimfonetuk (r) and our head of contacts mrs. tochi aguiyi-akujua @lynongod at the launch. 
violence against women in elections is not just a violation of the civic rights of women to vote, be voted for, or participate in the electoral process at various levels, it is a denial of their rights to be part of a free, fair and inclusive democracy. these incidents must be addressed because womenâ€™s rights are primarily human rights. -

text:
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

text: five former nfl cheerleaders are suing the houston texans saying that they would like full compensation for a hostile work environment. the women accused the franchise of paying them less than $7.25 an hour (equal to less than minimum wage in some states), being harrassed, not paying them for public appearances or other tasks like signings, and threatening to fire them for voicing their complaints and having opposing opinions. in wake of the #metoo movement, itâ€™s easy to think that the fight for womenâ€™s rights is being resolved. this case shows that women in the workplace (large and small industries) continue to fight for equal rights and pay. this story especially shows how women are seen in male dominated areas, such as the sports industry, and how they are not seen as women who are allowed to speak up and say when they are being mistreated. #ecstorytellers

text:
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

text:
tw: sexual violence. @emiliekrajcik shares her experiences with sexual violence and the impact it has had on her life.ğŸ’œ part 1.
â€œthree years ago, i was sexually assaulted by someone i knew. at time, i did not recognize this as assault. regardless of my conscious awareness of what happened, it shook me to the core. i felt very confused and disoriented about this experience. i had told a friend about the encounter immediately after it happened. several months later after doing research on the topic of assault i confided in her that i felt it was assault or even rape. so i â€œchanged my storyâ€ so to speak. she saved all of our messages and began showing them to people including the perpetrator. saying i am a â€œdelusional little girl who just got rejected.â€
this was my friend of ten years, who knew all of my friends, family, lived down the road and worked with me every day at the same restaurant. she mentioned this incident to our group of friend, acquaintances, co-workers and even my boss. so this caused me the loss of my social circle, indirectly cost me my job because i was not comfortable working there anymore, and also tension at home because it was a strain on my whole family. that is a severe consequence for simply telling the truth and not only that, it is absolutely unnecessary.
i paid off all my debts and moved from barrie to toronto in search for a safe place to be, and a fresh start. i began searching for creative outlets and found photography. shortly after i moved, the â€œme tooâ€ movement began. with all these stories and information available to me, i realized that what happened to me was extremely wrong and that i am not alone. i thought going through it that i was the only one and nobody would ever be able to understand. i was wrong.
i spent all my time and money doing research and developing my craft as a photographer so i could find a way to express what happened. i thought that if i shared my story it could help someone.â€œ (to be continued) #ourwomensvoices

text:
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

despite the difficulties, i am stronger now. i have new standards, boundaries and a higher purpose in life. i do not take for granted my health and happiness and i am better for it. i believe this was a pa of my spiritual journey and that i am here to help other women through their experience. i am working towards creating a membership program which will facilitate female friendships, educate women on their rights, advocate for them, and provide them with counselling. i really would like to provide both traditional and non-traditional approaches to healingâ€

text:
need to share this today. those from nz know about the story of grace who was allegedly murdered recently while back packing through our beautiful country. this article is so on point i want to print it out and make a wall paper of it.

https://thespinoff.co.nz/society/10-12-2018/rules-wont-save-women/. what will you be teaching your boys? i'm so glad i have a little boy who will be raised with the same standards as his older sister. growing up in a patriarchal community with different rules for boys and girls and constantly hearing that it's ok because he is a boy i am extremely aware of the need to not discriminate based on gender. every where i turned i was told not to do something or dress a particular way because the boys..it was also my fault when we were groped or assaulted. so teach our boys right. grow strong kind men. avoid comparison. do not make sexist jokes in front of your kids. and for goodness sake never say to your boy " why are you behaving like a girl?" as if it were the worst thing on earth. 
#motherhood #feminism #respect #boymom #stronggirls #reality #equality #nz #genderneutral #itsnotok #rules #takesavillage #sons #life #quotes #liferules #parenting #parenthood #mom #violence #metoo #rules #patriarchy #daughters #teachright #aucklandmom #freedom #brave

text:
@regran_ed from @sheforumafrica -  itâ€™s been a week of accelerated effort and commitments to end violence against women in all its forms. 
we participated at an interactive session on ending violence against women in elections. kudos to @unwomen @unwomen_africa @unwomennigeria on the launch of the programming guide on ending violence against women in elections (vawe). in pic: nigeria country rep. un women, ms. comfort lamptey with our founder @inimfonetuk (r) and our head of contacts mrs. tochi aguiyi-akujua @lynongod at the launch. 
violence against women in elections is not just a violation of the civic rights of women to vote, be voted for, or participate in the electoral process at various levels, it is a denial of their rights to be part of a free, fair and inclusive democracy. these incidents must be addressed because womenâ€™s rights are primarily human rights. -

text:
sadness used to be paralyzing, shameful, and debilitating. but now sadness is just a feeling... it is not who i am.
i feel excited. (i am whole.)
i feel nervous. (i am whole.)
i feel happy. (i am whole.)
i feel sad. (i am whole.) when we ask, "how are you?" notice that the question is not who are you? you are not defined by your feelings. you are whole even if you want to cry your eyes out.

moving louder means moving with these feelings, not against them. we dare you to name your feelings while knowing your wholeness.

text:
all i've ever wanted was to 'make it in new york.' i oft need reminding how hard i've worked to get where i am today & to celebrate every step of my journey.

i've had a grand series of success leading volunteer events, strut out on one date after another in killer heels, even after cutting my feet on glass from a self-made travel gallery wall, loved & lost beloved, survive #metoo every damn day, struggle to make that paper for the liberal arts degree loans and upgrade from queens to ues lifestyle, all the while keeping my smile intact.

it hasn't been easy. at tough times, the point of feeling like giving up, i think of my heroine scarlett o'hara as portrayed by vivien leigh. i recently made my first trip out west in cali to see her star... (swipeğŸ‘ˆ) if scarlett could come out on top as a savy business woman before her time, in a war torn country, with the love of her life and a killer wardrobe, so can i. after all, she'd say, "tomorrow is another day." i've never been more happy about my achievements and perseverance  than in this moment.

#killingit #workhardplayhard #humblebrag #dogood #itstheclimb #momentforlife #gonewiththewind #scarlettohara #iloveny #dontgiveup #hustle #respecttheprocess #thankyounext #thirtyflirtyandthriving #keepsmiling #dontworrybehappy

also on friday, the once-again head of breitbart told bloomberg news: - if thereâ€™s any confusion out there, let me clear it up: iâ€™m leaving the white house and going to war for trump against his opponents â€“ on capitol hill, in the media, and in corporate america.

the 63-year-old also retains the backing of hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer. the pair met on wednesday to plot their future plans, bloomberg reported.

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates suppoed by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

cu devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text:
this was a serious business, it was actually backed by goldman sachs, but it crashed and went bankrupt because the gamers themselves who weren't cheating became enraged basically that these other people were doing, they put so much pressure on the gaming companies. 
they put so much pressure on the video game companies, that they decided to basically ban gold-farming, which killed bannon's business, but it awakened him to the power of what he called "rootless white males" who spend all their time online. and five years later when bannon wound up at breitbart, he resolved to try and attract those people over to breitbart because he thought they could be radicalized in a kind of populist, nationalist way. and the way that bannon did that, the bridge between the angry abusive gamers and breitbart and pepe was milo yiannopoulous, who bannon discovered and hired to be breitbart's tech editor.

from the time i met him in 2011, he's had exactly the same politics. the same stuff you heard from trump, you saw on the campaign trail. what he was looking for was a vessel because nobody in republican washington believed in these kinds of ideas. the whole trend in the republican party was toward liberalizing immigration laws, passing comprehensive immigration reform. he was against it.

joshua green, author
devil's bargain: steve bannon, donald trump, and the storming of the presidency

text: sexual harassment and sexual assault are both issues prevalent in our society today. through the discussion the #metoo movement has created on social media and news media, these issues have gained considerable amounts of attention. the criminals have also been exposed and punished. however, there is still a serious need in our society for the creation of clearly defined rules regarding this matter. the best method to do so is by consistently discussing what is and isn't sexual harassment and sexual assault in order to create the fairest rules. #metoo -jiahua shen, ec3d, lecture 10

text:
this was a serious business, it was actually backed by goldman sachs, but it crashed and went bankrupt because the gamers themselves who weren't cheating became enraged basically that these other people were doing, they put so much pressure on the gaming companies. 
they put so much pressure on the video game companies, that they decided to basically ban gold-farming, which killed bannon's business, but it awakened him to the power of what he called "rootless white males" who spend all their time online. and five years later when bannon wound up at breitbart, he resolved to try and attract those people over to breitbart because he thought they could be radicalized in a kind of populist, nationalist way. and the way that bannon did that, the bridge between the angry abusive gamers and breitbart and pepe was milo yiannopoulous, who bannon discovered and hired to be breitbart's tech editor.

from the time i met him in 2011, he's had exactly the same politics. the same stuff you heard from trump, you saw on the campaign trail. what he was looking for was a vessel because nobody in republican washington believed in these kinds of ideas. the whole trend in the republican party was toward liberalizing immigration laws, passing comprehensive immigration reform. he was against it.

joshua green, author
devil's bargain: steve bannon, donald trump, and the storming of the presidency

text:
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

text:
one of the ongoing projects of #feminist #activism has been to bridge the public-private divide through which #women are confined to the 'private' realm -- such as homes, where their #labour is both used as the foundation of daily life, and devalued as not being 'real #work' and hence not deserving of pay. further, women are told that the '#privatespace' is the 'appropriate' #space for them, and the logic of '#safety' is used to justify this. 
in this poem yukta relates the experience of being a woman walking down the streets of #kathmandu and claiming that space. over the course of the poem she goes from wanting to be invisible, to wanting to be invincible. 
@yukta.bajracharya is a part of @wordwarriorsnepal, a kathmandu-based group of young #poets leading the #spokenword movement in #nepal. they aim to use spoken word as 'a regenerative and empowering tool to bring out stories and issues of the #nepali people, and utilize its potential to initiate #dialogue for social change'

listen to her poem here, and then come over to our stories to join the conversation this week. we are talking about public spaces, who gets to own them and the consequences that come with it.

text: (trigger warning) how truly beautiful it is when we are able to see our most painful experiences in a new light... whereas i once was ashamed for having stayed in an abusive relationship and for being a victim of sexual assault, i now see my past as a means by which i am learning to set healthy boundaries, discovering my limitless resilience, and developing a deep sense of self love and respect. i want to talk openly about these traumas in the hopes of letting other survivors know that you are not alone, that you do not have to struggle in silence, and that there is hope of healing. normalcy and stability will come again and while you wonâ€™t be able to return to the same person you were, itâ€™s because you will emerge a stronger, more enlightened, more radiant version of the you that you were always meant to be. through the darkness, you will shine âœ¨ #metoo #survivor #healing #youarenotalone #shameresilience #souljourney #selflove #safespace #psychopathfree #sunset #inspired

text:
strength: the quality or state of being strong; a good or beneficial quality of a person or thing.
*
* 
what strength is to me might look different than anothers. most people would not know i have been clean/sober going on six years now. that i can say "me too" with my head held high, or that at 24 years young my mother passed suddenly and i now provide for my 15 year old brother.
*
these events i have lived through! * 
we all have a story, a story we have lived through to see the next day! life its self can be cruel and deceitful. let us remember we do not have to act out the same; we can live through life with kindness, joy, and strength! * 
stand proud for yourself! your strength is unique to your person. surround yourself with others of strength and share your experiences.

text:
dipa karmakar is only the 5th women to have successfully developed the produnova, one of the most difficult vaults competed in women's gymnastics. 
born in a remote part of india and with flat feet, not many would have given her a chance to achieve what she did. 
dipa karmakar has truly nailed the fact that indian women can make anything happen with their dedication & courage. gymnastics, not so popular sport in india, took a turn for better when dipa karmakar etched india's name on the map of the world gymnastics after qualifying for the finals in rio. 
she is now, recipient of padma shri, rajiv gandhi khel ratna and arjuna awards.

sanfe salutes dipa karmakar's spirit to inspire young gymnasts to work and bring laurels to the nation.

because we have accepted to hide the abuse we suffer, because we have decided to be silent through the hurt. because we donâ€™t speak loud enough or often enough. because of the fear, the tears and the stares. but no more! 
it is time to hear me too, it is our time to stand up and fight against any abuse or violation of any girl, woman or child. we will no longer sit still and be silent. 
we will honour ourselves by standing up and speaking as we take back our power.

the time is now. it is time for change!
.
